    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1930-03-04T18:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1930-03-04T18:00:00-05:00" n="46"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d46">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.801 Search/10: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-03-04T18:00:00-05:00"
                            >March 4, 1930—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>83. Your telegrams 165, March 2, 11 a.m., and 166, March 3, 1 p.m. Department
                    believes that renewed representations to Nanking would be warranted protesting
                    against the stopping and searching of American merchant vessels by military
                    authorities. The Department suggests that the Chinese Ministry of Foreign
                    Affairs be reminded that the Chinese Maritime Customs is the agency of the
                    Chinese Government <pb facs="0191" n="93" xml:id="pg_93"/> authorized by treaty
                    to search American merchant vessels. Should the Legation’s representations be
                    ineffective in this instance, the Department should be so informed.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Cotton</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
